{{Infobox Japanese clan | name = Sanuki Inbe Clan (讃岐忌部) | crest = | crest_caption = | family_name = {{ill|Inbe (Imibe)|ja|忌部氏}} (斎部) {{ill|Sukune|ja|宿禰}} | founder = {{ill|Taokihonoho|ja|手置帆負命}} | type = {{ill|Shinbetsu|ja|神別}} ({{ill|Amatsukami and Kunitsukami|ja|天津神・国津神}}) | origin = | home_province = | notable_members = | branches = }}
The '''Sanuki Inbe Clan''' (讃岐忌部氏) is a branch of the {{ill|Inbe Clan|ja|忌部氏}}, distributed across various regions in Japan. They trace their ancestry to {{ill|Taokihonoho|ja|手置帆負命}}.
__TOC__{{-}}
== Overview == Taokihonoho, along with {{ill|Hikosashiri-no-Mikoto|ja|彦狭知命}}, cut sacred wood to construct the {{ill|Mizu-no-Mi-Araka|ja|瑞殿}}, a sacred palace, during the {{ill|Ama-no-Iwato|ja|天岩屋}} incident where {{ill|Amaterasu|ja|天照大神}} hid herself. This act led to Amaterasu emerging from the cave. Later, Taokihonoho served {{ill|Ōkuninushi|ja|大国主命}} as a {{ill|Kasanui|ja|笠縫}} during his descent.
The {{ill|Kogo Shūi|ja|古語拾遺}} (807 AD) mentions Taokihonoho as the progenitor of the Sanuki Inbe Clan, describing their role in crafting sacred bamboo poles (矛竿). These poles were annually offered to the imperial court, a tradition giving rise to the name "Sanuki" (竿調国).
The clan settled in modern-day {{ill|Mitoyo, Kagawa|ja|三豊市}}, where they developed the {{ill|Seisan Region|ja|西讃地方}}. According to shrine records, they collaborated with the {{ill|Awa Inbe Clan|ja|阿波忌部氏}} to cultivate hemp and develop the Sanuki Plain.
== Contributions to the Imperial Court == The Sanuki Inbe Clan provided bamboo poles as offerings, with records indicating contributions as late as Emperor {{ill|Sutoku|ja|崇徳天皇}}'s reign (1123–1142). According to the {{ill|Engishiki|ja|延喜式}}, they annually delivered 1,200 spears of sacred wood by November.
== Associations with Bamboo and Architecture == Taokihonoho's role as a craftsman of sacred structures has made him a patron deity of construction, particularly in {{ill|Jōtōshiki|ja|上棟式}} rituals.
== Connection to the Tale of the Bamboo Cutter == The Sanuki Inbe Clan is linked to {{ill|The Tale of the Bamboo Cutter|ja|竹取物語}}, with suggestions that its protagonist, {{ill|Sanuki no Miyatsuko|ja|讃岐造}}, was inspired by the clan. Historical artifacts and local events like the "Kaguya-hime Carnival" in Takamatsu further affirm this connection.
== Related Shrines in Kagawa Prefecture == * {{ill|Inbe Shrine|ja|忌部神社}} (Mitoyo City) * {{ill|Awa Shrine|ja|粟井神社}} (Kan'onji City) * {{ill|Ōasa Shrine|ja|大麻神社}} (Zentsūji City) * {{ill|Washi Shrine|ja|鷲尾神社}} (Mannō Town)
== Related Kofuns == * Gohon-so Kofun (Mitoyo City) * {{ill|Nodain Kofun|ja|野田院古墳}} (Zentsūji City)
