The '''Sanuki Inbe Clan''' (讃岐忌部氏) is a branch of the {{ill|Inbe Clan|ja|忌部氏|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, distributed across various regions in Japan. They trace their ancestry to {{ill|Taokihonoho|ja|手置帆負命|1=Sanuki Inbe clan|lt=Teokihobufu no Mikoto|2=ja|3=讃岐忌部氏|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
__TOC__{{-}}
== Overview == Taokihonoho, along with {{ill|Hikosashiri-no-Mikoto|ja|彦狭知命|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, cut sacred wood to construct the {{ill|Mizu-no-Mi-Araka|ja|瑞殿|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, a sacred palace, during the {{ill|Ama-no-Iwato|ja|天岩屋|qq=draft|qq=draft}} incident where {{ill|Amaterasu|ja|天照大神|1=Amaterasu|lt=Amaterasu Ōmikami|qq=draft|qq=draft}} hid herself. This act led to Amaterasu emerging from the cave. Later, Taokihonoho served {{ill|Ōkuninushi|ja|大国主命|qq=draft|qq=draft}} as a {{ill|Kasanui|ja|笠縫|qq=draft|qq=draft}} during his descent.
The {{ill|Kogo Shūi|ja|古語拾遺|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (807 AD) mentions Taokihonoho as the progenitor of the Sanuki Inbe Clan, describing their role in crafting sacred bamboo poles (矛竿). These poles were annually offered to the imperial court, a tradition giving rise to the name "Sanuki" (竿調国).
The clan settled in modern-day {{ill|Mitoyo, Kagawa|ja|三豊市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, where they developed the {{ill|Seisan Region|ja|西讃地方|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. According to shrine records, they collaborated with the {{ill|Awa Inbe Clan|ja|阿波忌部氏|qq=draft|qq=draft}} to cultivate hemp and develop the Sanuki Plain.
== Contributions to the Imperial Court == The Sanuki Inbe Clan provided bamboo poles as offerings, with records indicating contributions as late as Emperor {{ill|Sutoku|ja|崇徳天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft}}'s reign (1123–1142). According to the {{ill|Engishiki|ja|延喜式|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, they annually delivered 1,200 spears of sacred wood by November.
== Associations with Bamboo and Architecture == Taokihonoho's role as a craftsman of sacred structures has made him a patron deity of construction, particularly in {{ill|Jōtōshiki|ja|上棟式|qq=draft|qq=draft}} rituals.
== Connection to the Tale of the Bamboo Cutter == The Sanuki Inbe Clan is linked to {{ill|The Tale of the Bamboo Cutter|ja|竹取物語|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, with suggestions that its protagonist, {{ill|Sanuki no Miyatsuko|ja|讃岐造|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, was inspired by the clan. Historical artifacts and local events like the "Kaguya-hime Carnival" in Takamatsu further affirm this connection.
